In article &lt;KARL.90Mar12163053@giza.cis.ohio-state.edu&gt; karl@giza.cis.ohio-state.edu (Karl Kleinpaste) writes:
&gt;Anything stopping network hostmasters from creating their appropriate
&gt;zero-address entries within in-addr.arpa already?

This would make sense, but those entries are already used to identify
gateways to other internets.  Thus:

    Script started on Mon Mar 12 17:41:12 1990
    % nslookup
    Default Server:  localhost
    Address:  127.0.0.1

    &gt; set query=ptr
    &gt; 8.IN-ADDR.ARPA
    Server:  localhost
    Address:  127.0.0.1

    8.IN-ADDR.ARPA      host name = BBN2-GW.BBN.COM
    8.IN-ADDR.ARPA      host name = WB-GW.BBN.COM
    8.IN-ADDR.ARPA      host name = ENET1-GW.BBN.COM
    8.IN-ADDR.ARPA      host name = ENET2-GW.BBN.COM
    &gt; ^D
    % 
    script done on Mon Mar 12 17:41:37 1990

                           :: Jeff Makey

